A lot of your current checks are ad-hoc: They work for specific edge-cases, but not in a general case. With recursion, there are two important things to have: a base case (where you stop recursing), and a recursive step. If we consider the problem on its face, we can consider starting at the end, with a base case being that we found a non-zero element:

    public static int findTrailingZeroes(int[] arr) {
        return findTrailingZeroes(arr, arr.length - 1);
    }

    //Returns the total number of trailing zeroes from &#39;pos&#39; or earlier
    private static int findTrailingZeroes(int[] arr, int pos) {
        if (arr[pos] != 0) {
            return 0; //we found nothing in this step!
        }
        //TODO: Recursive step, which calls #findTrailingZeroes again
    }

So now we have an algorithm which will start at the end of the array, stopping when it finds a non-zero character. Notice that &quot;stopping recursion&quot; is the same as not calling your own method again. Now, in considering the recursive step, after the `if` statement we know that the current position is a `0`. So, at least at this position, we knows there&#39;s exactly `1 + rest_of_zeroes` zeroes from here towards the start of the array. Further, `rest_of_zeroes` can be calculated (by definition of our method) via `findTrailingZeroes(arr, pos - 1)`, so that&#39;s our recursive step!

    public static int findTrailingZeroes(int[] arr) {
        return findTrailingZeroes(arr, arr.length - 1);
    }

    //Returns the total number of trailing zeroes from &#39;pos&#39; or earlier
    private static int findTrailingZeroes(int[] arr, int pos) {
        if (pos &lt; 0 || arr[pos] != 0) { //Notice the addition of &#39;pos &lt; 0&#39;
            return 0; //If &#39;pos &lt; 0&#39;, then we hit the end of the array, no more counting!
        }
        return 1 + findTrailingZeroes(arr, pos - 1);
    }

In the end, as you recurse over the array, you&#39;ll end up &quot;counting&quot; the zeroes:

    arr = [1, 2, 3, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]
    Depth  Expression
    1      1 + rest
    2      1 + 1 + rest
    3      1 + 1 + 1 + rest
    4      1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + rest
    5      1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + rest
    6      1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 0
    Done

You don&#39;t really need to sum up anything. Just subtract `pos` from the `array length - 1`.  
